<DOC><DOCNO> AP881216-0177 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-16-88 1852EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-16 0478</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0487</SECOND><HEAD>Inclement Weather Dominates Both Coasts</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The sand dunes of Cape Hatteras, N.C., got some rare snow Fridayand Southern California endured a second day of snow, rain and highwinds, but the nation's midsection had mostly sunny, clear weather.   In addition to coastal North Carolina, parts of northeasternSouth Carolina also got some snow and sleet. Heavier snowfall duringthe six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST included 3 inches at New Bern,and 2 inches at Hatteras, Wilmington and Cherry Point, all in NorthCarolina.   Snow and winter weather advisories were still in effect for thenorthern and central coastal areas and the outer banks of NorthCarolina.   In Southern California, snow ended in the lower elevations butcontinued in the mountains. A winter storm warning was extended forthe San Bernardino mountains northward, with a snow advisory for thehigher deserts of Southern California. A wind advisory issued forthe mountains of San Diego County.   Mount Wilson, Calif., has received more than 3.5 inches ofprecipitation since the storm began Thursday, most of it rain.   A low pressure system moved across northern Minnesota toward theGreat Lakes, spreading light snow from eastern North Dakota to theUpper Mississippi Valley. Gusty northwest winds caused blowing anddrifting snow in eastern North Dakota and northwest Minnesota. Gustswere clocked at 43 mph at Alexandria, Minn.   Travelers to the Northeast should expect of significant snowfallexpected over the weekend from New York City through much of NewEngland as a storm developed along the East Coast, the weatherservice said.   Although inclement weather dominated both coasts, the nation'smidsection enjoyed mostly sunshine and clear skies Friday.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 4degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 80 degrees at Fort Lauderdale, Fla.The morning low for the nation was 18 degrees below zero at WestYellowstone, Mont.   Saturday's forecast called for snow throughout most of NewEngland and into northern parts of the Middle Atlantic Coast. Snowalso should extend from the northern and central Appalachians acrossthe upper Ohio Valley into the Great Lakes. Rains also shouldcontinue over much of central and Southern California. Fog and lowcloud cover was expected over Washington and Oregon.   High temperatures should be in the teens and 20s from the NorthAtlantic Coast across the upper Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes and theupper half of the Mississippi Valley to eastern parts of thenorthern Plains. Highs should range in the single digits overnorthern Minnesota and northwest Wisconsin. Highs should warm intothe 50s and 60s from Florida across the Gulf Coast, most of Texas,southern New Mexico and the desert Southwest to most of California,climbing into the 70s over parts of southern Florida. Elsewherehighs in the 30s and 40s should be the rule.</TEXT></DOC>